---
/**
 * Hub: child & dependent care credit. Worked example by dependentCareCredit().
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import DependentCareCalculator from '../../components/calculators/DependentCareCalculator.tsx';
import { dependentCareCredit } from '../../lib/credits';
import { formatMoney, formatPct } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const low = dependentCareCredit(6000, 2, 15000);
const mid = dependentCareCredit(6000, 2, 25000);
const high = dependentCareCredit(6000, 2, 60000);
---

<Base
  title="Child care tax credit calculator 2026 — dependent care"
  description="Estimate the 2026 child and dependent care credit: 20–35% of up to $3,000 (one child) or $6,000 (two or more) in care costs, by income. Non-refundable."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Child &amp; dependent care credit calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">A credit for paying someone to care for your kids so you can work.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    If you paid for child care — daycare, after-school, day camp, a nanny — so you
    (and a spouse) could work, the child and dependent care credit returns 20% to
    35% of it. Eligible costs are capped at {formatMoney(3000)} for one qualifying
    person and {formatMoney(6000)} for two or more, and the rate falls as income
    rises. It is non-refundable.
  </p>

  <DependentCareCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example — {formatMoney(6000)} of care for two children</h2>
  <p>
    The expense cap is the same at every income; the rate is what changes:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Income</th><th>Rate</th><th>Credit on {formatMoney(6000)}</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>{formatMoney(15000)}</td><td>{formatPct(low.rate)}</td><td>{formatMoney(low.credit)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>{formatMoney(25000)}</td><td>{formatPct(mid.rate)}</td><td>{formatMoney(mid.credit)}</td></tr>
      <tr><td>{formatMoney(60000)}</td><td>{formatPct(high.rate)}</td><td>{formatMoney(high.credit)}</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    At {formatMoney(15000)} the rate is the full 35%, worth {formatMoney(low.credit)}.
    It drops one point for every {formatMoney(2000)} of income above {formatMoney(15000)},
    reaching the 20% floor by about {formatMoney(43000)} — so most working families
    land at 20%, or {formatMoney(high.credit)} on {formatMoney(6000)} of costs.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How much is the child and dependent care credit?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      Between 20% and 35% of eligible care costs, capped at {formatMoney(3000)} for
      one qualifying person and {formatMoney(6000)} for two or more. The maximum
      credit is therefore {formatMoney(1050)} for one and {formatMoney(2100)} for two
      at the top rate, falling to {formatMoney(600)} and {formatMoney(1200)} at the
      20% floor.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How does the rate phase down?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      It starts at 35% for incomes up to {formatMoney(15000)} and drops one
      percentage point for each {formatMoney(2000)} of income above that, stopping at
      a 20% floor. There is no upper income limit — even high earners get 20%.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Is this credit refundable?</h3>
    <p>
      No. It reduces the tax you owe but is not paid back if it exceeds your tax. If
      your tax is already zero, the credit does nothing — unlike the earned income
      credit or the refundable part of the child tax credit.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>What expenses count?</h3>
    <p>
      Care for a child under 13, or a spouse or dependent unable to care for
      themselves, that lets you work or look for work: daycare, a nanny, before and
      after-school programs, day camp. Overnight camp, school tuition and care by
      your own dependent do not count.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Can I use this and a dependent care FSA?</h3>
    <p>
      Partly. Money run through a dependent care FSA cannot also be claimed here,
      and the FSA reduces the {formatMoney(6000)} cap dollar for dollar. Many
      families use the FSA first, then claim the credit on any remaining eligible
      costs up to the cap.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/child-tax-credit-calculator/">Child tax credit calculator</a> — the bigger per-child credit</li>
    <li><a href="/earned-income-credit-calculator/">Earned income credit calculator</a></li>
    <li><a href="/paycheck-calculator/">Paycheck calculator</a> — model a dependent care FSA</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Estimate for the 2026 tax year. Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
